ompelling portrait of how Americans used, wasted, and worried about natural resources in a time of burgeoning empire. Countering traditional narratives that cast conservation as a purely domestic issue, Tyrrell shows that the movement had global significance, playing a key role in domestic security and in defining American interests around the world. Tyrrell goes beyond Roosevelt to encompass other conservation advocates and policy makers, particularly those engaged with shaping the nation’s economic and social policies—policies built on an understanding of the importance of crucial natural resources. Crisis of the Wasteful Nation is a sweeping transnational work that blends environmental, economic, and imperial history into a cohesive tale of America’s fraught relationships with raw materials, other countries, and the animal kingdom.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aConservation of natural resourcesxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aConservation of natural resourceszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  awaste, problem, crises, garbage, empire, empirical, leadership, leader, president, theodore roosevelt, america, american, united states, usa, history, historical, green, environment, environmentalism, conservation, global warming, climate change, progressive, 1900s, resources, sustainable, sustainability, foresting, forestry, restrictions, hunting, nature, natural world, economy, advocacy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022619776040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226197937423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226197937/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles